23/10/2003
BUCHAREST, Romania -- Prime Minister Adrian Nastase met with investigators from Europe's anti-fraud office (OLAF) on Wednesday (22 October) and said "very tough" sanctions would be imposed on those who use EU money inappropriately or in violation of contractual terms.
He told OLAF representatives about measures undertaken by the government to prevent and combat corruption and economic crime.
In other news Wednesday, European Commission delegation chief Jonathan Scheele expressed regret over the resignation of Hildegard Puwak as minister for European integration, but said corruption allegations required action.
(Radio Romania Actualitati, Rompres, BBC, Mediafax - 22/10/03)
